Mar 3 2009 	Location Location Location	We stayed at the Ascot for 2 nights in February and were extremely grateful it was only for 2 nights. As mentioned in previous reviews, there was no-one at the desk when we arrived. He was actually outside having a cigarette and had decided not to follow us in. This was a common theme. Either that or there would be a few members of staff at the desk who had just decided to ignore you. Our room was not ready but we were advised that they had a &quot;luggage room&quot; available if we wished to leave our bags - this turned out to be a cupboard in the dining room that anyone could have access to and was piled high with bags and suitcases.The hotel itself is pretty grim. As also previously mentioned there is a peculiar smell in the entire building that they have attempted to mask with multiple plug in air fresheners. The whole building is extremely run down - carpets are worn, dirty and torn, plug sockets and various wires hang from the walls, the walls have holes in them, the ceilings also have holes and are sagging with damp in places and the corridors are generally filled with bags of rubbish and excess pieces of furniture (fold- away beds etc). You can't help but pray that you don't need to escape from the building in a hurry. Our room was actually a decent size - a double and a single bed and had the obligatory plug in air freshener. It was as run down as the rest of the hotel and unlike other reviews had obviously not been cleaned before we went in. The lock on our door did not appear particularly trustworthy, the cups were filthy and the shower was a disgrace. In fact you would have thought that it was actually in the process of being renovated - half of the tiles appeared to have just been put on and the rest looked like they were about to fall off. The bed sheets appeared to have been changed but were still dusty. We also discovered that a chair in the corner of the room was actually the only thing holding the curtains up as well! That was quite amusing when we moved the chair and the whole thing fell down! The electrics were a bit odd - you had to press a combination of switches in order to turn the main light on and off and out of the 3 bulbs on the lamp only 1 of them actually worked. The roof had patches of damp, particularly above the lights and there was a distinct rustling that I wouldn't have been surprised to discover was rats. You could hear the underground regularly but that wasn't actually too much of a problem and you have to expect some noise in central london. We didn't hear much noise from other rooms although the hotel in general appeared pretty quiet whilst we were there so that may differ when it's busy. Reading previous reviews, it also appears that we may have been placed in the staff bedroom (210), so perhaps we were lucky that we weren't actually near the staff on our stay.Although we were offerred a continental breakfast we didn't actually try it - the fact that the cups in our room weren't clean was enough to put us off attempting to eat there. There was a hairdryer that worked in our room and we had no problems with the TV. The only good thing about this hotel was the location. It is a five minute walk from Paddington station and so has easy access to Heathrow. It's also a 5-10 minute walk from Kensington Gardens and Hyde Park. One staff member was relatively helpful when we enquired about transport , even booking a taxi for us, although this appeared to be a friend of his and we don't know London well enough to know whether he took advantage, he did take a lot of side roads and dropped us off a good bit from our destination although admittedly there were a fair bit of roadworks.All in all, we won't be returning to this hotel any time soon. It's in a great location and served ok simply as somewhere to lie down at night but there's no way we would have stayed there for longer than 2 nights.	
